        "user": "What is a Token Tax?",
        "assistant": "# Token Tax\n\nA **token tax** is a fee or percentage automatically deducted from transactions involving a cryptocurrency token. It's coded directly into the token's smart contract, meaning the tax is applied every time someone buys, sells, or transfers the token.\n\n## How It Works\n\nWhen a transaction occurs, a predetermined percentage (commonly 1-10%) is taken from the amount being transacted. This happens automatically through the smart contract—no manual collection required.\n\n## Common Uses for Token Taxes\n\n1. **Liquidity Pool Funding** – A portion is added to the liquidity pool to stabilize trading.\n2. **Marketing Wallet** – Funds are directed to a wallet used for promoting the project.\n3. **Reflections/Rewards** – Taxes are redistributed to existing token holders as a reward for holding.\n4. **Buyback and Burn** – The project uses tax revenue to buy tokens off the market and burn them, reducing supply.\n5. **Development** – Funds ongoing project development and team operations.\n6. **Charity** – Some tokens donate a portion to charitable causes.\n\n## Buy vs. Sell Tax\n\nMany tokens have different tax rates for buying versus selling:\n- **Buy tax** is often lower to encourage purchases.\n- **Sell tax** may be higher to discourage dumping and reward long-term holders.\n\n## Things to Watch Out For\n\n- **Honeypots** – Some malicious tokens have a near-100% sell tax, meaning you can buy but can't sell.\n- **High taxes** – Excessive taxes (over 10-15%) can hurt profitability and indicate a riskier project.\n- **Hidden taxes** – Always check the contract or use tools like Etherscan, BSCScan, or honeypot checkers before investing.\n\nToken taxes are most common on networks like **BNB Chain** and **Ethereum**, particularly with meme coins and community-driven projects.",
