        "user": "What is a Token Tax?",
        "assistant": "# Token Tax\n\nA **token tax** is a fee automatically deducted from cryptocurrency transactions involving a specific token. The tax is built directly into the token's smart contract, so it's collected every time someone buys, sells, or transfers the token.\n\n## How It Works\n\nWhen a user transacts with a tokenized asset that has a tax, a percentage of the transaction is automatically redirected before the recipient receives their tokens. For example, if a token has a 5% tax and you buy $100 worth, you'd actually receive $95 worth of tokens, with $5 going to a designated wallet or function.\n\n## Common Uses of Token Taxes\n\n1. **Liquidity Pool Funding** – A portion is added back to the liquidity pool to stabilize trading.\n2. **Marketing & Development** – Funds project growth, advertising, or developer salaries.\n3. **Reflections/Rewards** – Redistributed to existing token holders as a passive income mechanism.\n4. **Burn Mechanism** – Tokens are sent to a burn address, reducing total supply (deflationary).\n5. **Charity/Treasury** – Allocated to a charitable cause or project treasury.\n\n## Types of Taxes\n\n- **Buy Tax** – Applied when purchasing the token.\n- **Sell Tax** – Applied when selling (often higher to discourage dumping).\n- **Transfer Tax** – Applied when sending tokens between wallets.\n\n## Pros and Cons\n\n**Pros:**\n- Funds project development without external capital\n- Rewards long-term holders\n- Can stabilize price through automatic liquidity\n\n**Cons:**\n- Reduces effective trading returns\n- Can be abused by malicious developers (e.g., **honeypot scams** where the sell tax is set to 100%)\n- Higher costs for active traders\n\n## Important Caution\n\nAlways check a token's tax structure before buying. Tools like **Token Sniffer**, **Honeypot.is**, or **DEXTools** can reveal hidden taxes and help avoid scam tokens with extreme or hidden fees.",
