        "user": "What is a Token Tax?",
        "assistant": "# Token Tax\n\nA **token tax** (also called a transaction tax or transfer fee) is a fee automatically deducted whenever a cryptocurrency token is bought, sold, or transferred. It's coded directly into the token's smart contract, so the tax is taken at the moment of the transaction.\n\n## How It Works\n\nWhen you transact with a taxed token, a percentage of the amount is automatically diverted before the rest reaches its destination. For example, with a 5% buy tax, purchasing $100 worth of tokens means you'd actually receive $95 worth.\n\n## Common Uses\n\nThe collected fees are typically routed to:\n\n- **Liquidity pools** – to maintain trading depth and price stability\n- **Marketing wallets** – to fund promotion and development\n- **Treasury/dev wallets** – for ongoing project work\n- **Reflections** – redistributed to existing holders as rewards\n- **Burns** – tokens destroyed to reduce supply\n\n## Typical Tax Structures\n\n- **Buy tax**: applied when purchasing\n- **Sell tax**: applied when selling (often higher to discourage dumping)\n- **Transfer tax**: applied on wallet-to-wallet moves\n\nRates commonly range from 1% to 10%, though some projects use much higher rates.\n\n## Things to Watch Out For\n\n⚠️ **Risks include:**\n- **Honeypot scams** – tokens with extremely high or hidden sell taxes (sometimes 99%+) that prevent you from selling\n- **Mutable taxes** – contracts where developers can change tax rates after launch\n- **Slippage issues** – taxes can cause failed transactions on DEXs if slippage tolerance isn't set high enough\n\nAlways check a token's contract on tools like Etherscan, BSCScan, or Token Sniffer before buying to verify tax rates and whether they can be modified.",
