        "user": "How does \"Token Tax\" differ from token cost / API cost-per-token?",
        "assistant": "# Token Tax vs. Token Cost (API Pricing)\n\nThese two terms sound similar but refer to completely different concepts in different industries. The word \"token\" means something distinct in each context.\n\n## Token Tax (Crypto)\n\n- **Industry**: Cryptocurrency / blockchain\n- **What \"token\" means**: A unit of digital currency or asset on a blockchain (e.g., an ERC-20 token)\n- **What it is**: A fee built into a smart contract that's deducted during buy/sell/transfer transactions\n- **Who collects it**: The token's project (routed to liquidity, marketing, holders, etc.)\n- **Purpose**: Fund the project, reward holders, discourage selling, or burn supply\n- **Measured in**: Percentage of transaction value (e.g., 5%)\n\n## Token Cost / Cost-Per-Token (AI/LLM APIs)\n\n- **Industry**: Artificial intelligence, specifically large language model (LLM) APIs like OpenAI, Anthropic, Google, etc.\n- **What \"token\" means**: A chunk of text the AI processes — roughly ¾ of a word in English. The sentence \"Hello, world!\" is about 4 tokens.\n- **What it is**: A usage-based price you pay per token sent to or received from the model\n- **Who collects it**: The AI provider (OpenAI, Anthropic, etc.)\n- **Purpose**: Bill customers for compute resources used during inference\n- **Measured in**: Dollars per million (or thousand) tokens, often split into:\n  - **Input tokens** – text you send (prompts, context)\n  - **Output tokens** – text the model generates back (usually priced higher)\n\n## Quick Comparison\n\n| Aspect | Token Tax (Crypto) | Token Cost (AI API) |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Token\" refers to | A blockchain asset | A unit of text |\n| Charged when | Buying/selling/transferring | Sending or receiving text from a model |\n| Set by | Smart contract code | API provider's pricing tier |\n| Typical unit | % of trade | $ per 1M tokens |\n| Goal | Project funding/tokenomics | Pay for compute usage |\n\n## Example Side-by-Side\n\n- **Token tax**: You buy $100 of CoinXYZ with a 5% buy tax → you receive $95 worth of CoinXYZ.\n- **Token cost**: You send a 1,000-token prompt to GPT-4 and get a 500-token response → you're billed for 1,500 tokens at the model's rate.\n\nIn short: a **token tax** is a transactional fee on a crypto asset, while **token cost** is a usage fee for AI text processing. They share a word but live in entirely different worlds.",
